{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537622"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:18:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:18:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16034"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16034"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.04,0.03,0.15,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63615"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8725"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"5594"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20868"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63615"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy is admitted to hospital with gastroenteritis requiring nasogastric tube insertion for rehydration. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. During insertion of the nasogastric tube, he develops sudden onset respiratory distress with wheeze and increased work of breathing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 160/min, respiratory rate 60/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has widespread wheeze on chest auscultation with intercostal recession and nasal flaring.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue nasogastric tube insertion","Administer adrenaline","Administer salbutamol","Give supplemental oxygen","Remove nasogastric tube"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents an acute bronchospasm triggered by nasogastric tube insertion, a known complication due to vagal stimulation. The immediate priority is to remove the stimulus causing the respiratory compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemove nasogastric tube\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as it will eliminate the trigger for bronchospasm. Vagally-mediated bronchospasm typically resolves quickly once the stimulus is removed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister salbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary if bronchospasm persists after removing the nasogastric tube, but it is not the first step. The priority is to remove the triggering stimulus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGive supplemental oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate to treat hypoxia, but again, this should follow removal of the nasogastric tube. Treating the underlying cause takes precedence over symptomatic management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for bronchospasm caused by vagal stimulation. This would be more appropriate for severe anaphylaxis or severe croup.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue nasogastric tube insertion\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous as it would prolong the bronchospasm and respiratory compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter removing the tube and allowing the child to settle, subsequent attempts at nasogastric tube insertion should include pre-treatment with topical anaesthetic and careful explanation to parents. Alternative methods of rehydration might need to be considered if repeated attempts are unsuccessful.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nasogastric tube insertion can trigger vagal responses including bronchospasm, laryngospasm and bradycardia.","Immediate removal of the nasogastric tube is essential if respiratory compromise occurs during insertion.","Pre-treatment with topical anaesthetic can reduce the risk of vagal responses during nasogastric tube insertion."],"references":["Edwards LR, Borger J. Pediatric Bronchospasm. [Updated 2023 Jun 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546685/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16034"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49062"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T19:36:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T19:36:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8725"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63615"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posi